Also,  by owing a tower, doing a soft-reset is a easy as pressing one button
as opposed to the old way of a 3-key Amiga keyboard press, just think of the
times you've been on your miggy and one of your mates phones up, during your
conversation you need to do a soft-rest for whatever,  do you  (A)   try  to
balance  the phone on your shoulder and end up looking a bit like Quasimodo,
or (B)  end up by putting the phone down to perform the reset,  or (C) get a
bloody soft- reset button fitted to your A1200,  or wire up the one in  your
tower  if you've got a tower but haven't bothered or known how to  wire  the
reset button up.
@1
During a phone-call to Tom Spicer a while ago,  I found out that  he  had  a
tower,  but didn't know how to wire up the little soft-reset button  on  the
front of the tower,  ans if my memory serves me correctly, it was me who was
one  of  the first lads in our days with The Crypt diskmag to use this  hack
successfully,  I do know from experience that this little hack can  be  used
to wire up existing tower soft-reset buttons,  or hacked onto a bog-standard
A1200 case,  and truthfully speaking, if you've got an ounce of intelligence
(which  I haven't as my mate Snoopy tells me more often than not)   most  of
you who need such a device can perform the hack yourself,  a soldering iron,
and  some  solder and a steady hand is all that is required as  far  as  the
physical  side  of  things go,  and a basic knowledge of soldering  is  also
required for the task.



The hack can be done in one of two ways,  having said that,  the second  way
involves  soldering  two  very   fine   wires  onto  the  U13  chip  on  the
motherboard,   and  although I've done both variations  at  different  times
during  my days on the my A1200,  I'll stick to the simplest way  this  time
for you, ok.
@6
So for none tower owners I won't bore you all with the obvious details about
opening up your miggy etc,  that is common sense,  isn't it??,  so with your
miggy  opened up and your keyboard and bits removed in order to expose  your
A1200's  motherboard you need to look at the lower left hand corner  of  the
motherboard,  by the PCMCIA slot,  you'll see two rows of solder blobs named
as TP1 and TP2,  our hack revolves around soldering two small wires onto the
first two solder at the far left of TP1,  it doesn't matter which way  round
the wires go,  just so long as they only go on the first two leftmost solder
blobs, but be careful not tow run solder onto any of the other blobs.

OK,  so you've soldered to small short wires to the two blobs,  I would  now
advise  you to connect a small double plastic juntion block onto  these  tow
wires after you've stripped and tinned both wires (people who do a fair  bit
of  soldering  will  understsnd  those  terms,   next,   you  need  a  small
subminature "MAKE SWITCH",  not a normal switch, a "Make" switch is one that
"Makes"  a circuit complete by a single press,  but also "Breaks"  the  same
circuit on release of the same button,  a "Make Switch" will cost you a  few
pence I think from most Tandy's store,  or from Maplins, or most hobby shops
that deal in basic electronics.

Now,  the two wires that you've just connected to the plastic junction block
both need to be soldered onto the contacts of the "Make Switch",  then  tidy
up  the  two wires and wrap a few bits of insolating tape aound the  two  of
them not to isolate them because they should already be isolated,  but so as
to keep them both neat and kept together while at the same time you need  to
decide  which  direction  your  going  to  feed  them  over  or  around  the
motherboard  so as to somehow fit this subminature "Make Switch"  onto  your
A1200  case  somewhere that's going to handy and within easy reach  to  you,
when  that's  all  done,  reconnect all the bits back onto the  motherboard,
such  as  the  keyboard etc,  but at this stage don't put  your  A1200  case
together yet just in case of problems.
@1
Power  up  your miggy,  then with a light push on the new button your  miggy
should  hopefully  reset itself,  if all works ok then diconnect  everything
again,  power lead etc, then finish off by putting your migghy back together
again,   and  hopefully you'll now have fitted a fully  working  soft  reset
button,  tower owners only need to solder two wires onto the motherboard the
same  as the standard A1200 users,  then terminate these two wires with  the
same  type  of junction block,  then wire up the two wires from your  towers
soft  reset  button and your in business,  no more hassles  with  trying  to
reset your miggy whilst on the phone, sorted geezer.

Some  people say that the miggy is dead,  some say that it's far from  dead,
but  even  me as a true blue-bloodied Amiga supporter will stick  his  kneck
out  and say that the miggy we all once knew is not so much dead nor  is  it
alive as we once remember it,  I will say that due to modern technology  and
the  need  for faster and more powerful CPU processors and new DOS operating
systems,   the  miggy has had to adapt or be adapted into  a  new  millenium
machine in order to live on......

With  the birth of a new PC/Amiga clone of which I've just read about,  this
is  the nearest thing that us older Amiga users will ever see again in their
days of a new type of Amiga,  when the first miggy especially the A1200  was
first  created,  computer technology was in it's infancy,  some  years  have
passed and with the development of the big PC's,  the miggy has had to adapt
itself  in  order to still be a worthwhile machine for people to still  use,
and  although  things in the recent past with Escom and  Gateway  2000  both
bottling out due to lack of financial gain,  Bill and "Shaggy Carpet (as Ray
Hawkins now calls him)  have taken over and with a joining up with  Tao  and
the  like,   it  now  seems as though our prayers for a new  reliable  Amiga
saviour to help up has finally come into being,  the only price we've had to
pay  is  losing  the status symbol "Shape" of the miggy we've  all  come  to
know, but as we all know, with progress come change.

@2
I  personally think that at first in my earlier days on the miggy it  was  a
bloody good machine with an even better design and shape,  but my views have
changed  with  upgrades and add-ons such as bigger hard  drives  which  mean
miggy  need to have more power,  hence built into towercases now,   graphics
cards seems to be the new "In-Thing",  again,  more power is needed for  the
old  miggy  together with more space,  so a tower is now more of a necessity
that  an  upgrade,  well,  that if you want to stay in touch with the  miggy
scene  for  as long as possible,  if not,  then keep your old A1200  as  you
first bought it and fall behind.

Upon  making contact recently with a bloke who advertised in Micro Mart  for
any  A1200  users to please write to him with help on  how  to  sort  out  a
problem with and old word processor called Word Perfect I contacted the  guy
(name with held obviously),  I was stunned to find out that in this day  and
age he was only using a 1Mb A600 and two floppy drives,  no hard drive,  was
this bloke lost or what,  anyway,  after a good hour or so chat on the phone
to  him  one  Saturday or Sunday,  It soon became apparent that although  he
wanted  to  upgrade to a better machine,  he didn't have or know  the  right
sources in who to ask for help from,  anyway,  I made a quick phone call  to
one of my contacts who was selling a complete A1200 system that had the  lot
in order to just plug and go,  decent hard drive,  8Mb Ram card,  A1200, etc
etc,  the price was sensible, about £250 inclusive of p&p I think, anyway, I
phone  this  new contact back,  told him the deal,  gave him my own  contact
phone number and left the rest to the both of them to work out the deal,   I
then  get  a phone call from my own contact saying that this new lad  passes
on  his thanks to me for sorting out such a good deal,  and the deal was now
signed and sealed,  and that my contact would soon be getting the money  for
the whole package, great I thought.
